        "where $\\hat{\\sigma}^2 = T^{-1}\\sum e_t^2$ is the variance of the one-step errors. Maximizing this is equivalent to minimizing the sum of squared one-step errors — which is also what we would get from least squares. The difference with full MLE is that the initial states are estimated as free parameters rather than set by convention, and that the likelihood framework extends naturally to prediction intervals and model comparison via AIC.\n",
