        "The train-test exercise illustrates a lesson that comes up repeatedly in forecasting: a model's out-of-sample performance during a period containing an extreme event tells us more about the event than about the model. The 2020 collapse and recovery are simply outside the support of anything a time series model estimated on postwar data could anticipate. The more informative question — how well does the model forecast in normal times, across many short windows — is what rolling-window and pseudo-real-time evaluation procedures address. We return to those methods in Chapter 5.\n",
