        "\n",
        "The tools developed in this chapter serve as a practical foundation that will be enriched considerably in the chapters that follow.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Chapter 3** provides the theoretical justification for much of what we have done here on intuitive grounds. Simple exponential smoothing is the optimal forecast for an ARIMA(0,1,1) process; Holt's method corresponds to ARIMA(0,2,2); Holt-Winters corresponds to a seasonal ARIMA model. These are not coincidences — the entire ETS family sits inside the ARIMA family as a set of restricted special cases. When we fit an ETS model by maximum likelihood, we are implicitly estimating a restricted ARIMA. Understanding the ARIMA representation unlocks better tools for model selection, residual diagnostics, and the construction of prediction intervals. It also provides the formal machinery for the Beveridge-Nelson decomposition, which separates a unit-root process into its permanent and transitory components — offering a model-based answer to the same trend-cycle separation problem we approached statistically in this chapter, with no free smoothing parameter and a cycle uniquely pinned down by the estimated ARIMA model.\n",
